"{\"uid\": \"metro.co.uk-2024-08-12-tom-daley-announces-retirement-diving-following-paris-olympics-21407605\", \"text\": \"Team GB legend Tom Daley has announced his retirement from diving afterwinning a silver medal at this summer's Paris Olympics.  Daley, 30, was selected as one of Team GB's flagbearers for the opening ceremony, alongside rower Helen Glover, ahead of his fifth consecutive appearance at an Olympic Games.  After making his Olympic debut aged just 14 at the Beijing Games in 2008, Daley went on to establish himself as one of the most recognisable faces in British sport.  The silver Daley won alongside Noah Williams in the men's synchronised 10m competition was the fifth medal of his long Olympic career, after three bronzes and the gold he clinched in Tokyo three years ago.  Speaking toBritish Vogue, Daley revealed that he had already made the decision to call it quits before adding another medal to his sizeable collection in the French capital this summer.  'It feels very, very surreal. I felt so incredibly nervous going into this, knowing it was my last Olympics,' Daley said.  'There was a lot of pressure and expectation. I was eager for it to be done\\u2026 but when I walked out, and saw my husband [Dustin Lance Black] and kids [Robbie and Phoenix] and my friends and family in the audience, I was like, you know what? This is exactly why I did this.  'I am here, and no matter what happens in the competition itself, I am going to be happy.'  Sorry, this video is not available any more.  After representing Great Britain for over half of his life, an 'emotional' Daley said it 'feels like the right time' to retire.  'It was emotional at the end, up there on the platform, knowing it was going to be my last competitive dive,' he added.  'But I have to make the decision at some point, and it feels like the right time.  'It's the right time to call it a day.'  Daley made headlines across the world when he publicly came out as gay in December 2013 and the diver is glad to see increasingly more athletes do the same in recent years.  'With every Olympics, there are more and more out athletes. It's powerful,' he continued.  'I think there is a lot of pressure for when people do come out to be an activist and to be outspoken. And sometimes that's just not in some people's nature. I think this might be part of the reason why possibly more people have not felt as comfortable with coming out.  'I also think that [the world of sport] is such a heteronormative space\\u2026 lots of queer kids, when they are younger, have this automatic feeling that they should not fit into sports, so they do not pursue them. I hope we will see more in the future.'  Daley spent the second half of the Games providing punditry for Eurosport and the four-time world champion is interested in pursuing a career in front of the camera.  He went on: 'I have also enrolled in a class, a course at the Fashion Institute of Design and Merchandising (FIDM) in Los Angeles, to be able to learn how to sew.  'I knit and I crochet, but sewing will just add a whole different level of knowledge as to how to construct things.  'I have actually designed a couple of pieces of underwear that I am going to be launching, and then I am also hoping to launch a swimwear project next year.'  For more stories like this,check our sport page.  Follow Metro Sport for the latest news onFacebook,TwitterandInstagram.  ArrowMORE:Team GB star Tom Daley reveals he accidentally left his silver medal behind in Paris' Olympic Village  ArrowMORE:Noah Lyles' mum blasts Paris Olympics for leaving son with covid 'gasping for air' after race  ArrowMORE:Most memorable and controversial moments of the Paris Olympics after a wild ride in the French capital  Punchy analysis, transfer talk and more from Metro's football experts, sent straight to your inbox every week.  Let us know which team you support.Close  This site is protected by reCAPTCHA and theGoogle Privacy PolicyandTerms of Serviceapply. Your information will be used in line with ourPrivacy Policy  Punchy analysis, transfer talk and more from Metro's football experts, sent straight to your inbox every week.  Let us know which team you support.Close  This site is protected by reCAPTCHA and theGoogle Privacy PolicyandTerms of Serviceapply. Your information will be used in line with ourPrivacy Policy\"}"